Part I - Loan Data From Prosper¶

by Isaac Ninson¶

Introduction¶

This project seek to explore some variables on 113,937 Loan Borrowers records.Loan Borrowers are identified by a unique key and there are 81 different information captured on each Borrower. I will explore 14 variable out of the 81.

At the end of the exploration, I expect data to confirm some norms and also I hope to discover some unsual or suprising relationships among the variables

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset has 113,937 entries with 81 columns which provide varied information on Borrowers on the loan platform. 75% of the columns are numeric, 21% string and 4% bool data types. 53% of the columns have missing values

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

My main features of interest are;

  1. Prosper Rating - Prosper Rating assigned to Borrowers
  2. Term - The Tenure of the Loan
  3. Is Borrower Homeowner - Confirmation on whether a Borrower is a home owner or not
  4. Listing Category - This provides the various reasons Borrowers apply for loans

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The following columns will enable me explore my features of interest;

  1. MemberKey - This is a unique for Borrowers
  2. EmploymentStatus - This specify the Employment Status of Borrowers at the time of loan application
  3. IncomeVerifiable - Borrower indiates whether their source of income is verifiable
  4. StatedMonthlyIncome - The Montly Income indicated by a Borrower
  5. IncomeRange - The range in which a Borrower's income falls
  6. DebtToIncomeRatio - The Borrower's Debt to Income Ratio
  7. LoanOriginalAmount - The origination amount of the loan
  8. MonthlyLoanPayment - The scheduled monthly loan payment
  9. LoanOriginationQuarter - The quarter in which the loan was originated
  10. Borrower APR - The Borrowers Annual Percentage Rate (APR) for the loan

Observations¶

  1. New dataset has some missing values.
  2. From the variable definition, Listing Category(numeric) is a boolean data but not an integer.
  3. Term which is Loan Duration can be reclassified to take a string data.
  4. There are duplication in the MemberKey column which is suppose to be a unique key for each borrower. These observations shall be treated at the data cleaning stage

#Estimate the proportion of null values excluding the ProsperRating COlumn

#Create a list of columns with null values except
null_columns = ['EmploymentStatus','DebtToIncomeRatio','BorrowerAPR',]

# Estimate the number of null records in each column with a list comprehension
null_counts = [df_Newloan_clean[col].isnull().sum() for col in null_columns]

# Calculate the total proportion of null values in the dataframe
null_proportion = sum(null_counts) / df_Newloan_clean.shape[0]

print('The combined percentage of null records is ' + str(null_proportion * 100)[:4] + '%')

The combined percentage of null records is 9.36%

Remarks¶

  1. The proportion of missing values in EmploymentStatus, DebtToIncomeRatio and BorrowerAPR is 9.36%. I can therefore drop these missing values.

Observations¶

  1. Borrower APR appears to be normally distributed but with peaks around 0.09, 0.2 and 0.3. It however has a sharp peak between 0.35 and 0.37. There is a few of the Borrowers that had APR greater than 0.4
  2. Loan Amount is negatively skewed. It shows that majority of the loan amounts were below USD 15,000 with most of them within the region of USD 5,000 and USD 10,000.Loan Amount around USD 4,000 had the highest count, followed by USD 15,000 and then USD 10,000.
  3. Monthly Loan Payment is negatively skewed.It shows that majority of the Monthly Loan Payment were below USD 400 with a few beyond USD 800.Most of the Borrowers made a monthly payment within USD 150 and USD 200.
  4. Debt to Income Ratio is negatively skewed.It shows that majority of the Borrowers' ratio were between 0.15 and 0.25 with a few beyond 0.75.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

  1. Borrowers are postively skewed on Prosper Rating. More than 50% of Borrowers rated C or higher

  2. Borrowers were postively skewed on Loan Terms. Majority of the Borrowers went for Medium to Long Term loans.

  3. Although there was difference in number of Borrowers who owned home and those who did not, the difference isn't significantly huge.

  4. I didn't identify any unsual point regarding my variables of insteres neither did I transform any of the variables.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

I had unsual distribution on the following variables; Loan Original Amount, Monthly Loan Payment and Debt to Income Ration. I therefore adjusted the ticks of these variables to enable me have a better view of the distribution since the original data didn't show ticks for the bins intervals.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

  1. As the number of homeowners increases, the ratings increases from low to high ratings. However after rating C, the number of homeowners begins to fall from B to AA but this fall is still higher than those without home.

  2. As ratings increases from low to high, the number of high income erners increases.

  3. Loan Amount and Monthly Loan Payment were positively related while the two variables inturn had a negative relation with Borrower APR and Debt to Income Ratio.

  4. Prosper Rating had a positive relation with Loan Amount but a negative relation with Borrower APR

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Loan Amount and Monthly Loan Payment has negative relation with Borrower APR. This is surprising because I expect the cost of borrowing thus the APR to be increasing with an increasing loan amount.

sb.pointplot(data=df_Newloan_clean,x='ListingCategory', y='BorrowerAPR',order=None,hue='IsBorrowerHomeowner',linestyles = '-.')
plt.legend()
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.show()

Observation¶

BorrowerAPR are lower for Homeowners than Non-homeowners for all the listing category except Household Expenses

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

  1. Monthly Loan Payment decreases as Loan Term and Loan Amount increases. This conforms to the norm as it is expected that with a a longer loan term, Borrower pays less amount than a short term and diffently as the loan amount increases, the term is expected to increase else the monthly payment will be very high in order to pay off loan within a short period.

  2. Borrower APR decreases as Ratings and Loan Term increases. This is understandable since Loan Term has a positive relation with Loan Amount which inturn has a negative relation with Borrower APR and Ratings has a negative relation with Borrower APR

  3. Homeowners took higher loan amount largely for debt consolidation. While Non-homeowners took high loan Amount (lower than that of Homewoners) largley for purchase of Boat. As Prosper Rating increases and Loan Amount increases, Homeowners and Non-homeowners diverges. This means Homeowners with higher ratings takes higher Loan Amount done Non-homeowners with same ratings

  4. Among my features of interets Prosper Rating and Loan Term had a positive relation thus they strenthened each order

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

  1. Borrowers took Long Term Loans for Weddings, Baby&Adoption and Engagement Ring. This I find surprising because these are categories are events and not a long term activity.

Conclusions¶

  1. It was discovered that a larger proportion of the borrowers took loan for the purpose of Debt Consolidation. A further finding revealed that Debt Consolidation had the higest loan amount and this was secured by Homeowners.
  2. Having a good rating and sametime being a homeowner have great positive influence on the Loan Amount and Loan Term that a Borrower can secure. This is fair since a good rating and suggest a borrower has the ability to pay loan and also having a home serves as a significant collateral to secure loan.
  3. I investigated the listing category to find the most popular loan terms for the various listing.Except Student Use which Borrowers did only Medium Term, Borrowers did not have any particular Loan Term preference for the remaining categories. It was therefore surprising to found out that Borrowers took Long Term Loans for Weddings, Baby&Adoption and Engagement Rings since this are considered to be mostly a one off event that rearly re-occure in one's live.
